Task 1 – Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic

Tool Used
Canva (canva.com) — free browser-based design and infographic tool.
What the Design Shows
The infographic is titled "Be a Digitally Literate Student" and is structured as a single-page visual resource divided into three sections:
What is Digital Literacy?
The ability to find, evaluate, create, and communicate information using digital technologies.
Includes knowing which tools to use, how to use them safely, and how to present yourself online.

Safe Internet Practices
Use strong, unique passwords for every account.
Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) wherever available.
Avoid clicking unknown links in emails or WhatsApp messages (phishing).
Do not use public Wi-Fi for banking or logging into sensitive accounts.

Professional Online Presence
Keep your LinkedIn profile updated with your education and skills.
Maintain a clean GitHub with your projects and a profile README.
Think before you post — your digital footprint is permanent.

Reflection

For this task, I used Canva to design a one-page Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic. Canva was the right choice because it offers ready-made infographic templates, drag-and-drop editing, and free PNG export — all without requiring any prior design experience or software installation.
My infographic covers three topics that I believe are most immediately relevant to a first-year engineering student: what digital literacy actually means, how to stay safe online, and how to build a professional digital presence. I kept the text concise and used icons to make each point visually distinct, so the infographic works as a quick-reference resource rather than a wall of text.
The most challenging part of this task was deciding what not to include. Digital literacy is a broad subject, and the temptation to cover everything — cybercrime, coding tools, cloud storage, academic integrity — made it hard to stay focused on a single page. I found it interesting to practise the discipline of prioritisation: identifying the three or four points that would have the biggest impact on my batchmates and letting everything else go. This is a skill that transfers well beyond design.
